Constant group: TEST_MESSAGE_TYPE
Description: The different types of test messages
Constant name Type Value Comment
RESETint1Resets an order book to an original state.
SYNCint2Purely a pass-through. Used by the test application to make sure that the entire result of a message have been drained from the system.
INFORMATIONint3Purely a pass-through. Used to make the transactions easier to navigate.
METAint4Used to inject meta data into transaction monitor logs. If testMessageType is META, the String in the info field will be printed in the transaction monitor logs.
PUBLISHint5Informs ME to trigger a call to CD to republish orders to the ME. For test purposes only.
CURRENTint6Tells ME to count the number of orders in an orderbook. EmapiTestEvent returns the number of currently active orders in ME. For test purposes only.
Constant group: ORDER_EVENT
Description: The different types of order events.
Constant name Type Value Comment
INSERTint1Insert of new order. The order data contain the new order.
CANCELint2Cancellation of existing order. The order data contains the order as it looked at the time of cancellation.
UPDATEint3Update of order. The order data contains the modified order. Note that all fields are included not just the one modified. NOTE! In case of an incoming update request to ME the orderQty field is always interpreted as relative. The resulting outbound request will however as normally contain an absolute value.
Constant group: QUOTE_EVENT
Description: The different types of quote events.
Constant name Type Value Comment
INSERTint1Insert of new quote. The quote data contain the new quote.
CANCELint2Cancellation of existing quote. The quote data contains the quote as it looked at the time of cancellation.
UPDATEint3Update of quote. The quote data contains the modified quote. Note that all fields are included not just the one modified.
Constant group: ORDER_EVENT_SUBTYPE
Description: The different types of order event sub types.
Constant name Type Value Comment
RESTOREint1An GDT/GTC order previously saved persistently has been restored in preparation for a new trading session.
EXPIREDint2A order has expired since its validity period has ended. A typical example of an expiring order is a GDT/GFD order that is purged at the end of the trading session.
PARTIALLYFILLEDint3Order was partially filled
FILLEDint4Order was completely filled.
MASSACTIVATEDint5Order was part of a mass activation.
MASSUSPENDint6Order was part of a mass suspension
MASSCANCELint7Order was part of a mass cancellation
MEMBERUSERDISABLEDint8The order changed status since a user or member was disabled.
USERDELETEDint9The order changed status since its user was deleted.
USERDISCONNECTEDint10The order changed status since its user lost its connection.
UPDATEint11The order was updated.
INSERTint12An explicit insert by the user.
CANCELint13An explicit cancel by the user
SAVEDOVERNIGHTint14A GDT/GTC order was canceled since it was saved overnight. It will be restored once the next trading cycle begins i.e. typically the next day.
WOULDHAVECROSSEDint15In some market models it is not allowed to cross one's own order. In such a case a previously entered order might be canceled with this order event sub type.
PRICERECALCULATEDint16The price has been recalculated; for instance a peg order has been re-priced by the system.
ORDERCONDITIONint17The order changed status due to an order condition being triggered. A typical example is a stop-loss order.
NO_BASE_PRICEint18The order changed status due to a base price being unavailable. A typical example is an order pegged to an external market. In this case the base price used to price the peg order is provided by a link to the external market. If the link goes down then the base price becomes unavailable.
CANCEL_DUE_TO_PRICE_BANDint19This subtype signals that an order is canceled due to a price band break.
RESTORE_VALIDATION_FAILEDint20A long order failed validation at reinsert, i.e. would have resulted in a reject if the order was inserted through a request.
CANCEL_DUE_TO_TRADING_PROTECTION_LIMITint21The order was canceled due to the trading protection limits.
CANCEL_DUE_TO_CORPORATE_ACTIONint22The order was canceled due to a corporate action.
CANCEL_DUE_TO_DISABLED_ORDERBOOKint23The order was canceled because the orderbook is no longer available for trading.
CANCEL_DUE_TO_ORDER_VALIDATION_FAILint100The order was canceled due to the order validation.
Constant group: STATE_EVENT
Description: The different types of state events
Constant name Type Value Comment
STATE_CHANGE_OBint1New state. An order book changed state. Note that in some system configurations order book state changes are suppressed on order book level. In such cases state changes will only be disseminated on order book rule group level.
STATE_CHANGE_OB_RULEGROUPint2New state. An order book rule group changed state. Once the order book rule group has changed state the individual order books belonging to that order book rule group will start to change state. Typically the state changes of the order books are spread out over a period of time. Thus it normally takes some time before all order books in the order book rule group have changed state.
UNXint3UNX has been initiated. Any trades/order updates associated with the uncross will follow immediately after this message.
SAVE_LONG_ORDERSint4Save of long orders process has been initiated. Long order will be stored persistently and removed from the current order book. Any order cancel associated with this process will follow immediately after this message.
DELETE_EXPIRED_ORDERSint5Deletion of expired orders has been initiated. Expired orders are either GTD orders with today's date or day orders. Any order cancel associated with this process will follow immediately after this message.
PUBLIC_ORDERBOOK_OBSOLETEint6The contents of the public order book are invalid and should be discarded. Any client application should make sure to empty their public order book. This event is typically generated when an order book changes transparency.
HALT_EVENTint7This orderbook state change message is related to halt; either halt being imposed or halt being lifted.
Constant group: TRADE_HALT_EVENT_TYPE
Description:
Constant name Type Value Comment
TRADE_HALTint1Trade halt.
TRADE_HALT_LIFTEDint2Trade halt lifted
PENDING_TRADE_HALT_LIFTint3A trade halt lift operation is to be executed at the next ordinary schedule change. The reason for this is that the configured uncross sequence could not fit into the time available until the next scheduled state change. Instead the trade halt lift operation occurs at the next state change. This trade halt type is generated by the system itself and can not be used when sending in trade halt requests. Thus it can not be used in TradeHaltReq message, but may occur in OrderBookStateChangeEvent message generated by the system.
TRADE_HALT_UPDATEint100Update of a trade halt reason, Note this is only used in incoming request.
Constant group: STATE_FREEZE_EVENT_TYPE
Description: Type of system state freeze event.
Constant name Type Value Comment
FREEZEint1System state scheduler have been frozen. This means that scheduled state changes will not be executed event though the time has passed the when they ordinarily are executed instead they are deferred for execution once the scheduler is thawed.
UN_FREEZEint2System scheduler has been thawed. Any deferred state changes will immediately be executed.

Constant group: PRICE_CONDITION
Description:
Constant name Type Value Comment
MARKETint1The order will, in Automatch, trade as much as it can and then be canceled. In Auction, it will be get the best price of "best price of the own side improved by one tick and the worst price on the opposite side". If the order is not completely filled in the Auction, the remaining quantity will be canceled. An application should never attempt to interpret the price or actualPrice field in an OrderEvent when this price condition has been set. In the OrderInsertReq message the price field must be set to null when sending in orders.
LIMITint2The order can be executed at the specified price or any better.
PEG_BEST_BIDint3The order should be pegged to the best bid. In the OrderInsertReq message the price field must be set to null when sending in orders. The actualPrice field in the OrderEvent message will show the current effective price of a pegged order.
PEG_BEST_OFFERint4The order should be pegged to the best offer. In the OrderInsertReq message the price field must be set to null when sending in orders. The actualPrice field in the OrderEvent message will show the current effective price of a pegged order.
PEG_MIDPOINTint5The order should be pegged to the midpoint between the best bid and offer. If the midprice does not fall on an even tick, round down. In the OrderInsertReq message the price field must be set to null when sending in orders. The actualPrice field in the OrderEvent message will show the current effective price of a pegged order.
MARKET_TO_LEVELint6If the order is entered during continuous trading, the order will, upon entry, be priced to the best available price on the opposite side of the book. If the order is not filled it will be booked at this price. If the order is entered in an auction phase, it will get the best price of "best price of the own side improved by one tick and the worst price on the opposite side". If the order is not filled in the auction, the order will be booked at the uncross price after the uncross, provided that the order did not already have a price before the auction started. In non auction phase, the price used will be reflected in the actualPrice field.
SPECIAL_MARKETint100A market order will buy or sell as much as possible of the order volume at best available price. The remaining volume of the market order will be converted into a limit order at one tick better than last traded price. If there are no prices in the orderbook and the market order cannot match, it will be cancelled.
Constant group: VALID_FROM
Description: The Valid From condition
Constant name Type Value Comment
IMMEDIATEint1The order is immediately entered into the market. This is the default.
TRIGGERint3The order becomes inactive until the trigger condition has occurred. See TRIGGER_CONDITION and triggerPrice.
GOOD_FROM_TIMEint4The order becomes inactive until the specified time has passed. The time is always relative to the current day, and if the time has passed, then the order is activated immediately. The time is specified in the validFromData field using the format HH:mm:ss. Note that the system internal clock may not have a millisecond resolution. The order will be activated at the next time check when the timer is found to have expired. This time check may not happen more frequently than once a second depending on system and configuration.
GOOD_FROM_NEXT_AUCTIONint6The order becomes inactive until the next auction. It participates in equilibrium price calculations broadcast before the uncross.
GOOD_FROM_NEXT_AUTOMATCHint7The order becomes inactive until the next automatch session. It participates in equilibrium price calculations broadcast before the uncross.
GOOD_FROM_SESSIONint8The order becomes valid when the specified session starts. If the current session has the specified name, then the order is immediately entered into the market if other conditions so permit. If a session with the specified name has already passed during the current session cycle, then the order remains and waits for the next session with the specified name. The session name is specified in the ValidFromData field and is simply a text string reflecting the name of the relevant state and example might be Open.
Constant group: VALID_DURING_CONDITION
Description: Specifies during which events and sessions that the order is valid
Constant name Type Value Comment
ALLint1There are no restrictions. The order is valid between the time it becomes valid until it either expires or is filled.
AUTOMATCH_ONLYint2This order is only valid during Automatch states. It does not participate in any auctions.
AUCTION_ONLYint3This order is only valid during Auction phases. This means that it is not valid during Automatch. It becomes valid during auctions only.
Constant group: VALID_TILL
Description: The validity period of an order.
Constant name Type Value Comment
NEXT_MATCHint1The order is valid till it has had one chance of matching. During automatch, the order therefore behaves like a FOK or FAK order. During an auction phase, this condition is not valid and the order will be rejected.
GOOD_TILL_TIMEint2The order expires automatically when the specified time has been reached. The time is always relative to the current day, and if the time has passed, then the order is canceled immediately. The time is specified in the ValidTillData field using the following format HH:mm:ss or yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ss. Note that the system internal clock may not have a millisecond resolution. The order will be canceled at the next time check when the timer is found to have expired. This time check may not happen more frequently than once a second depending on system and configuration.
GOOD_TILL_NEXT_AUCTIONint3The order is canceled when the next auction session is entered. If the current session is an auction, then the order is canceled immediately.
GOOD_TILL_NEXT_AUTOMATCHint4The order is canceled when the next automatch session starts. This means that the order is valid during auction sessions. If the current session is in automatch, then the order is canceled immediately.
GOOD_TILL_SESSIONint5The order is canceled when the specified session starts. If the current session has the specified name, then the order is immediately canceled. If a session with the specified name has already passed during the current session cycle, then the order remains and waits for the next session with the specified name. The session name is specified in the ValidTillData field.
GOOD_TILL_DAYint6The order is good for the remaining part of the trading session. More specifically, the order remains until a session starts that is marked with the "expireDayOrders" flag.
GOOD_TILL_DATEint7The order is valid until a specified date. The date is specified in the ValidTillData field using the following format yyyy-MM-dd
GOOD_TILL_CANCELint8The order is valid until explicitly canceled.
Constant group: TRIGGER_CONDITION
Description: Different types of stop loss conditions.
Constant name Type Value Comment
ASK_OR_HIGHERint1Order is triggered if the best ask price is higher or equal than the trigger price.
ASK_OR_LOWERint2Order is triggered if the best ask price is lower or equal than the trigger price.
BID_OR_HIGHERint3Order is triggered if the best bid price is higher or equal than the trigger price.
BID_OR_LOWERint4Order is triggered if the best bid price is lower or equal than the trigger price.
LAST_PAID_OR_HIGHERint5Order is triggered if the last paid price is higher than or equal to the trigger price.
LAST_PAID_OR_LOWERint6Order is triggered if the last paid price is lower than or equal to the trigger price.
SHORT_SELLint7Order is triggered if the last paid price is higher (up tick) or equal (side tick) than the previous last paid price. There is no history between day so the second trade is the first one that can trigger short sell.

Constant name Type Value Comment

FIXEDint1Fixed discretionary price = Actual Price + discretionary offset capped by discretionary cap price.

Constant group: VISIBILITY
Description: Whether an order is transparent or dark
Constant name Type Value Comment
TRANSPARENTint1Order is visible in accordance with the market model. Typically a market model includes several different trading states (sessions) each with its own transparency level. If an order is TRANSPARENT it means that it is visible if the current transparency allows for it.
DARKint2Order is not visible.
Constant group: MINIMUM_VOLUME_CONDITION
Description: How the Minimum Volume Condition should affect matching
Constant name Type Value Comment
NONEint0This order has no minimum volume restriction. I.e. a partial executions can be as small as the current market model allows for (according to round lot etc.)
MULTIPLE_ORDERSint1This order do have a minimum volume condition attached to it, but is still willing to a accept partial executions as long as the aggregated traded volume during one matching event satisfies the minimum volume condition. A matching event is the atomic chain of events triggered by, typically, an incoming order.

Constant group: CACHE_ACTION
Description: Defined cache actions
Constant name Type Value Comment
ADDint1Add to cache EMAPI - interpret as Add

REMOVE_CACHE_FORCEDint7Remove from cache (does not remove object from db), removes even if there are references to object. The isDeleted attribute is set to BOOLEAN.TRUE EMAPI - interpret as Remove

Constant group: AllowedValidTill
Description: The validity period of an order.
Constant name Type Value Comment
GOOD_TILL_DAYint1The order is good for the remaining part of the trading session. More specifically, the order remains until a session starts that is marked with the "expireDayOrders" flag.
GOOD_TILL_DATEint2The order is valid until a specified date. The date is specified in the ValidTillData field using the following format yyyy-MM-dd
GOOD_TILL_CANCELint3The order is valid until explicitly canceled.
GOOD_TILL_AUTOMATCHint4The order is cancelled when the next automatch session starts. This means that the order is valid during auction sessions. If the current session is in automatch, then the order is cancelled immediately.
GOOD_TILL_AUCTIONint5The order is cancelled when the next auction session is entered. If the current session is an auction, then the order is cancelled immediately.
IOCint6Immediately - or cancel.
FOKint7Fill or kill.
GOOD_TILL_TIMEint8The order expires automatically when the specified time has been reached. The time is always relative to the current day, and if the time has passed, then the order is canceled immediately. The time is specified in the ValidTillData field using the following format HH:mm:ss. Note that the system internal clock may not have a millisecond resolution. The order will be canceled at the next time check when the timer is found to have expired. This time check may not happen more frequently than once a second depending on system and configuration
GOOD_TILL_SESSIONint9The order is canceled when the specified session starts. If the current session has the specified name, then the order is immediately canceled. If a session with the specified name has already passed during the current session cycle, then the order remains and waits for the next session with the specified name. The session name is specified in the ValidTillData field.
